@node Requirements "System Requirements"
@font Courier.font 15


     @{b}System Requirements@{ub}

@font Courier.font 13
  o  Any Amiga computer with SO 2.04 or above.
  o  MultiView with datatypes.
     Although not required this is the dafault.
     (Read @{"Tool Types" link ToolTypes} for more information).
  o  CBE will work with any program that uses Clipboard Unit 0.

  No other extra libraries or files are required.

@endnode

@node Installation "Installation"
@font Courier.font 15


     @{b}Installation@{ub}

@font Courier.font 13
  Just drag the CBE icon to any drawer, or copy CBE to the directory
where you wish it to run from.  The best place for this of course is
the WBStartup directory on you boot drive.

  That is it.  No additional libraries or handlers are required.

  You may want to keep the CBE.guide and @{"CBE.iff" link CBE.iff/main} files together.  You
may call up the @{"CBE.iff" link CBE.iff/main} image from the documentation, or with your
favorite viewer.

@endnode

@node Usage "Using CBE"
@font Courier.font 15


     @{b}Using CBE@{ub}

@font Courier.font 13
  Using CBE to recall previous pieces of clipboard data is almost as
easy to use as the Shell's review buffer.  The following is a more
detailed description of CBE's features and how to make them work.

  You can look at the @{"CBE.iff" link CBE.iff/main} file as a reference if needed, or you can
just run the program right now if you haven't already.

  o  What you probably notice first is the large Listview gadget
     containing the clipboard data.  Above that is a recessed box which
     displays the data of clipboard unit 0. (Since this is used by almost
     all programs, for simplicity I call it the activte unit.)

     If this is your first time running CBE, you will see '[##]:xx' where
     xx is a Hex value for the clipboard unit number shown.  This may not
     mean much to you, and if it doesn't, do not worry.  Some people
     requested to know exactly what was going on.

     As you Cut or Copy data from another program like @{b}CygnusEd@{ub}, or @{b}Final
     Writer@{ub}, you will see that the data you just clipped will be displayed
     in top two lines of the listview box.  The top line as stated
     earlier is the current or active unit.  The first line of the
     listview box is the first item in the history buffer.  Although
     under most conditions this will be identical, there will be times
     that these will not match up.

     You may scroll through the review list by using the scrollbar,
     by using the arrow keys, or by draging the mouse up or down off
     the the top or bottom of the box.

  o  To recall a previous clip to allow you to paste it back innto an
     application, select any item in the list, and move it to the @{b}TOP@{ub}
     of the list.  You may do this in two ways.  The easiest is by
     pressing the buttn labeled @{fg highlight}"TOP"@{fg text}, or you may press the button
     labeled @{fg highlight}"UP"@{fg text} until the item you selected is in the top position.
     The value of this item will then be copied into the active clip
     board unit, and will of course be displayed in the top reccessed
     box, showing that this item will be pasted whenever a Paste
     operation is done.
@{fg highlight}
     !!NOTE:  You cannot move an empty unit to the Top position, since
              no data is contained there what is the point.  This may
              cause some confusion if moving the Top item in the list
              would cause another to move into the active slot.
@{fg text}
  o  The @{b}UP@{ub}, @{b}DOWN@{ub}, @{b}END@{ub} buttons are merely there as a convienience, as
     their actions do not normally affect the active clipboard unit.

  o  Next to the active unit display box, you will see a [@{b}J@{ub}] button.
     This allows you to make the CBE window 'jump' to the screen
     behind the current one it is residning.
     This button is only active if you have turned on the ToolType
     @{"USEFRONTSCREEN" link ToolTypes}.
@{fg highlight}@{b}
     !!NOTE:   The @{"USEFRONTSCREEN" link ToolTypes} is not a system freindly option.
               See the @{"ToolTypes" link ToolTypes} section for more info.
@{fg text}@{ub}
  o  The "@{b}VIEW@{ub}" button allows you to see what is containned in the
     selected unit.

     CBE's display is a static 21 characters wide with 16 actually
     displaying what is in the clipboard unit.  If for some reason
     this is not enough for you to tell what is in the unit, press
     @{b}VIEW@{ub}, and Multiview will display whatever is there.
     MultiView is capable of automatically displaying text, images,
     or even playing sounds.  Use the Tool Types @{"TXTVIEW" link ToolTypes}, @{"GFXVIEW" link ToolTypes},
     and @{"SNDPLAY" link ToolTypes} if you do not have MultiView.
     If the tooltype @{"FIXFONT" link ToolTypes} is set to YES, the display will be a bit wider,
     normally about 24 bytes wide with 19 bytes of what is in the clipboard.

     The line displayed in the listview box contains 19 characters of
     the clipboard's data as well as the IFF type specification for
     that unit.  This will normally be FTXT for a text clip. But it
     may dislpay ILBM, or 8SVX and possibly others.  The latter may
     just have a file name in the display, so some form of 'viewing'
     is needed to know exactly what is there.
     The last character of the line will be set to a '@{b}»@{ub}' to show that
     there is more information than will fit within the ListView box.

     Double clicking on the item in the list will also View it.
     Viewing is done asyncronously, so you may view as many units as 
     memory allows.

  o  The @{b}CLEAR@{ub} button allows you to empty the selected clipboard unit.
     If you double click on the Clear button a requester will pop up
     asking @{b}FREE@{ub}, @{b}ALL@{ub}, or @{b}CANCEL@{ub}.  Selecting @{b}ALL@{ub} will clear out every
     unit in the clipboard including those that may be 'locked'.
     Selecting @{b}FREE@{ub} will only clear those that are not 'locked'.
     These will clear the active unit as well, so further Pasting will
     yeild no results until another Cut/Copy action is done.
     @{b}CANCEL@{ub} will return, but the selected unit will still be cleared.

  o  The Free/Lock cycle button allows the user to Lock or unlock any
     unit in the review list.  Locking a unit will keep CBE from
     selecting that unit for normal review storage.  Under normal
     use, this unit will no longer be changed.  The Reserved Key units
     start out locked.  Freeing a unit will allow it to be unsed when
     needed to store clipboard review history data.
     Locked units are signified by a '-' between the IFF specifier,
     and the clipboard data.  Else a ':' is displayed.
     See warnings/notes under @{"Reserved Keys" link ReservedKeys}.

  o  The Update button will free, and re-read all the clipboard review
     data to make the display current.
     CBE does not listen for changes on every clipboard unit available to
     the system, so it is possible for another program to alter the
     clipboard data of another unit (number 5 for example), and CBE
     will never know the data changed, so the review list will not
     change.  You can use Update to see this new data.
@{fg highlight}
     !!Note:  The system clipboard device saves all clipboard units
          1-255 to disk.  These files are saved in the logically
          assigned directory "CLIPS:".  This is worth noting in case
          you were to clip a lrge section of 24 bit ILBM data for
          example. This is a lot of data to keep on disk.
          Normally the s:Startup-sequence assigns this to RAM:
          If you assign CLIPS: to disk, these pieces of data will be
          there for you again when yoo even after you re-boot the system.
          If you choose to delete any of the files from this directory,
          you would want to press Update to reflect those changes.
@{fg text}
  o  In the lower left corner just above the CLEAR button you will see
     a box with a number in it.  This box tells the number of UNITS
     used to hold the review data.
     The Amiga has 256 clipboard units.  Unit 0 is considered the
     active unit so you cannot use that one of course.  This leaves up
     to 255 units for a review history.  CBE will not allow more than
     255 units, nor less than 3 just for the sake of usefullness.
     If you have some @{"Reserved Keys" link ReservedKeys} assigned, CBE will take some
     enough of these units for their use.  i.e.  if you have 4 keys
     assigned, CBE will require a minimum of 7 units.
     If you decrease the number of units used, the @{"Reserved Keys" link ReservedKeys} will
     now be moved to the end of the new range of units used.
     (The actual data is not moved!  See @{"Reserved Keys" link ReservedKeys} for more info.)
     
     See More Details for, well, err, uhmm, more details.

      One note of interest is that I felt that the clipboard access was
     very slow.  To read data from all 255 units takes more than 3
     seconds on my 50MHz 68030.  So the default is set to 30 only
     for reasons of speed.

  o  Pressing the Window's close gadget or by pressing the [ESC] key
     will bring up a requester showing various bit of information
     including regitration info.  The requester allows you to @{b}QUIT@{ub},
     @{b}CANCEL@{ub} or @{b}HIDE@{ub}.  The function of the first two are obvious.
     Selecting HIDE will cause CBE's window to close, but CEB will
     continue to function.  You may bring up the window again by
     pressing the hot key, or by using the Exchange commodity to
     show CBE's window.  The registered version hides CBE's window
     immediately when the Close gadget is clicked or [ESC] is pressed.

  o  CBE now has an @{"ARexx" link ARexx} port for more advanced system usage.
     See the @{"ARexx" link ARexx} section for full usage instructions.

  o  The menus allow the user to Quit, see an about window, as well as
     make CBE @{"Inactive" link ARexx 69}/@{"Active" link ARexx 76}, or the user can Hide the window.
     
  o  Some have suggested a ZOOM gadget.  I dont like the idea, but it
     took no work, and seems as though quite a few people wanted it.
     So now CBE can zoom down to a tiny window.  Note that ALL features
     of CBE still function.  You can use the cursor keys to select a
     Clipboard unit and View or even Clear it from the keyboard, althogh
     you will of course not be able to see what you are doing.
     (The registered version of CBE allows you to tell where the
      Zoom window will be placed.  Default is original starting location
      of CBE.)

  o  Open and Save do nothing in the un-registered version.  To do
     this now all you need to do is open a file using MultiView and
     select the menu item 'COPY'.  You can also save an item Viewed
     with MultiView, so for all intents and purposes, these are not
     a big loss to non-registered users.

@endnode

@node ToolTypes "ToolTYpes"
@font Courier.font 15


     @{b}Tool Types@{ub}

@font Courier.font 13
       The following tooltypes may be entered into CBE's icon info, or
     they may be used from the CLI/Shell.  When entering parameters
     from the shell, remember any arguments with spaces MUST be
     surrounded by double quotes (").
          e.g.  CBE  TOPUNIT=5  "COPY_KEY1=lalt ctrl c"

     CX_POPKEY   - Key used for HotKey to pop window up or to front.
     CX_POPUP    - Should interface window open on start. (YES/NO)
     CX_PRIORITY - Priority for input-event processing. (default -5)
     TOP    - Top edge for Window.  -1 for center on mouse. (default -1)
     LEFT   - Left edge for window. -1 for center on mouse. (default -1)
     ZOOMTOP     -  Where to put window when ZOOM gadget is pressed.
     ZOOMLEFT    -  -1=center on mouse.  @{b}(ONLY works on registered version)@{ub}
     TOPUNIT     - First clipboard uit to use for histroy.  (default 1)
     UNITS       - Number of units used for review buffer.  (default 30)
     TXTVIEW     - Full path name of file for
     GFXVIEW     -  you own text, graphics and
     SNDPLAY     -  sound viewers/players.
     COPY_KEY1...COPY_KEY10   \\  @{"Keys" link ReservedKeys} to use to copy or paste to/from
     PASTE_KEY1..PASTE_KEY10  /  reserved clipboard units.
     USEFONT     - Choice of SCREEN font or system DEFAULT fonts for display.
     FIXFONT     - Widens display for fonts with bad XSize information. (YES/NO)
     PUBSCRNAME  - Name of public screen for CBE to pop up on. Workbench as default.
     USEFRONTSCREEN - Will open CBE on the front most screen rather than
                       always on the default Public screen.  (YES/NO)
                       YES for this tooltype takes precedence over PUBSCRNAME.
@{fg highlight}@{b}
     !!NOTE:  that USEFRONTSCREEN  is NOT a system friendly method of doing things.
              you may cause system problems if you close a screen that CBE is open
              on.  You have been warned.
@{fg text}@{ub}
@endnode

@node ARexx "ARexx support"
@font Courier.font 15


     @{b}ARexx support@{ub}

@font Courier.font 13
  o  CBE now (as of Version 2.2a) has ARexx suppport.  The portname is
       @{fg highlight}CBERexx.1@{fg text}
     This ARexx support functions are rather simplistic, but give the
     user the capapbility to do anything he/she can do from the user
     interface.

  o  @{b}QUIT@{ub}
     No parameter are given.  CBE will simply clean up and exit.

  o  @{b}UNITS@{ub} [units]  :  units = number 3 through 255.  Same as @{"ToolTypes" link ToolTypes}.
     Allows the user to change the number of units needed by CBE.

  o  @{b}UP@{ub} [unit]  :  unit = 1 though UNITS.
     Move currently selected unit up one space if possible.
     If [unit] is given, that specified unit will be moved up.
     [unit] is relative to the displayed data, not based on actual
     system values!

  o  @{b}DOWN@{ub} [unit]  :  unit = 1 though UNITS
     Move currently selected unit down one space if possible.
     If [unit] is given, that specified unit will be moved down.
     [unit] is relative to the displayed data, not based on actual
     system values!

  o  @{b}TOP@{ub} [unit]  :  unit = 1 though UNITS.
     Move currently selected unit to the TOP.  Empty units cannot be
     moved to the top location of the list.
     If [unit] is given, that specified unit will be moved to the Top.
     [unit] is relative to the displayed data, not based on actual
     system values!

  o  @{b}END@{ub} [unit]  :  unit = 1 though UNITS.
     Move currently selected unit to the end of the list..
     If [unit] is given, that specified unit will be moved to the End.
     [unit] is relative to the displayed data, not based on actual
     system values!

  o  @{b}LOCK@{ub} [unit]  :  unit = 1 though UNITS.
     Sets the lock on the currently selected unit.
     If [Unit] is given, the specified unit will have it's lock set.
     [unit] is relative to the displayed data, not based on actual
     system values!

  o  @{b}FREE@{ub} [unit]  :  unit = 1 though UNITS.
     Frees the lock on the currently selected unit.
     If [Unit] is given, the specified unit will have it's lock freed.
     [unit] is relative to the displayed data, not based on actual
     system values!

  o  @{b}SELECT@{ub} <unit>  :  unit = 1 though UNITS
     Makes the specified unit the currently selected item.
     <unit> is required.
     [unit] is relative to the displayed data, not based on actual
     system values!

  o  @{b}VIEW@{ub} [unit]  :  unit = 1 through UNITS
     Views the currently selected item
     If [Unit] is given, the specified unit will be viewed.
     [unit] is relative to the displayed data, not based on actual
     system values!

  o  @{b}UPDAT@{ub}E
     Same as selecting the update button.  UPDATE will free and
     re-read all clipboard data.

  o  @{b}INACTIVE@{ub}
     Will deactivate CBE's commodity key input features.  These include
     The clipkeys, and hotkey window popup.  CBE will also not listen
     for changes inn the clipboard, so the list will not change.
     You are still allowed to use the GUI, and paset from the items in
     teh review list.    Same as INACTIVE from Commodities Exchange.

  o  @{b}ACTIVE@{ub}
     Will make CBE active again.  Same as ACTIVE in comodities Exchange.

  o  @{b}COPY@{ub} [unit]  :  1-10 (or as many keys defined).
     Copy will simply send an [RAMIGA-c] to the system.  If unit is
     Specified, CBE will copy the data into the specified ClipKey
     number.  [unit] is relative to the end of the list.

  o  @{b}PASTE@{ub} [unit]  :  1-10 (or as many keys defined).
     This will paset the current contents fo the active clipboard
     unit by sending an [RAMIGA-v] to the system.
     If [unit] is given, the spcified clipKey number will have it's
     data copied to clipboard unit 0 before the [RAMIGA-v] is given.
@{fg highlight}
     !!NOTE:  PASTE will ALWAYS paste from what is in unit 0.  Remember the
          clipkeys sequence first copies it's data into unit 0.  If
          simply do a PASTE again with NO unit specifier, the same data
          from the clipkey will be pasted again.  This offers some
          speed increase, but also possible confusion as you really do
          not know what might be in unit 0 at any given time this way.
          Also, CONCLIP (Commodore's solution to clipboard access
          through the shell) seems to be a quick HACK!  If you try to
          use ARexx COPY command for Shell highlighted text, it will
          not work.  The Shell must transmit the [RAMIGA-c] sequence
          somehow to the CONCLIP program.
@{fg text}
  o  @{b}WINDOW@{ub} <SHOW | HIDE | JUMP>
     This change the windows orientation.  SHOW will bring the window
     to the front of the frontmost screen.  The window will be opened
     if needed.  HIDE will close CBE's window, but let the main
     program remain active.
     JUMP will force the screen onto the next screen.  This will work
     from ARexx even if the user has the @{"USEFRONTSCREEN" link ToolTypes} set to NO.
     Use only when neccessary, remember this is NOT a nice thing to
     do to the system.  Although no damage is caused from normal
     operation, the danger comes in when a screen tries to close
     when it does not know about CBE being there.  The result of
     this action can range from a permanently open scren to a system
     crash.

  o  @{b}CLEAR@{ub} [unit | FREE | ALL]
     Clears the currently selected item.  If unit is given, the
     specified unit will be cleared.  [unit] is as above in VIEW, etc...
     FREE will clear all non-locked items.
     ALL will free evry item in the review list.

  An simple ARexx script has been included merely to allow the user to
test these features.

     CBERexx.rx:
  =-------- cut here -----------------=
     /*  CBE ARexx pport tester  */
     PARSE ARG CBEcmd

     ADDRESS CBERexx.1 CBEcmd
  =-------- cut here -----------------=

     Example Usage:    rx CBERexx.rx  WINDOW HIDE

@{fg highlight}
     !!NOTE:  One simple note to ARexx programming.  There is no locking
          mechanism throught the Amiga system for the clipboard device.
          What I mean is, just because you may do a COPY command and
          immediately follow it with a PASTE command, there is no 100%
          garauntee that the data will remain the same.  This is really
          only a concern if some one does not know what is going on,
          and they can clip data REALLY fast.
@fg text}
@endnode

@node ReservedKeys "Reserved keys"
@font Courier.font 15


     @{b}Reserved Keys@{ub}

@font Courier.font 13
  You may reserve up to 10 clipboard units for the use of quick access
key cut/copy/paste actions.

  As defaults, the function keys are used for these "clip keys" as I
call them for a lack of a better name.  You must use the @{"ToolTypes" link ToolTypes}s to
assign keys to any, all 10, (or none) of the units.  If you set a
COPY_KEY, you must set PASTE_KEY for the same number.  Failure to do
so will elliminate the use of both functions for either key without a
matching Copy/Paste key @{"ToolTypes" link ToolTypes}.

  All clipkeys reserve the last units in the review list.  These may
move depending on user actions, but the data will not be affected by
normal copy actions due to the locking feature of CBE.  If you unlock
any of the clipkey units, the data stored there may be changed when
another cut/copy action takes place.

  To use the clipkeys, just higlight the data in any application that you
want to copy.  (Do this in the normal way for the apllication in use).
When you press (default as an example...) [lalt shift f1], the data
will be copied into the active clipboard unit and it will also be copied
into the review list as normal, except instead of being put at the
head of the review list, the clipboard data is copied into the unit
specified by the key you pressed to do the copy action.

 i.e.  You have 5 keys reserved, f1-f5 with SHIFT ALT for Copy actions,
and lets say just for S&G's you have f6-f10 with the same qualifiers for
Paste actions.  Go to you application (CygnusEd is good), highlight
some text, and do [RAMIGA-c].  Do this a few times while CBE's window is
visible.  You will see the list change with each copy action.
Now highlight some text and press your [shift alt f4] key combination
and you probably will not see any changes except for the top reccessed
box showing that the active clipboard unit (0) has changed.  If you
pull the slider to go to the end of the review liist, you will see 5
locked units. One of them will have the data you just clipped.

 You may now do [RAMIGA-v] to paste as normal or [alt shift f6] to
paste the data back.  (Note f8 corresponded with the f4 above).
Now highlight and clip text the normal way using [RAMIGA-c], and you
will see the 'Free' part of the review list change, but you reserved
clipkey does not change.  Now you may press [alt shift f8] and paste
that reserved data back.   Pretty nifty eh?  You may of course move
this item to the TOP just as any other so paste in the normal way.
This is handy for custom Copy/Paste operations using @{"ARexx" link ARexx} from
another application I suppose.

The following are valid qualifies and keys  Just as for HotKeys:

     lshift    rshift    shift    (Left right, or either shift key)
     lcommand  rcommand           (Left or right Amiga keys)
     lalt      ralt      alt      (Left, right, or either Alt key)
     capslock  caps               (Capslock key, or ANY shift/capslock)
     ctlr                         (CTRL key)
     leftbutton midbutton rbutton (Mouse buttons)

     The following keys as well as any normal keyboard keys are valid:

     space backspace tab enter
     return esc del up down left  ( other misc keys  )
     right f1...f10 help

 You may be wondering excatly why CBE requires an application that
uses clipboard unit number 0 to work properly.  The reason is simple
in that all CBE does is set what are called "Call-back hooks" in the
system for Clipboard unit 0, so it "hears" all Cut/Copy actions to
that clipboard unit.  Also the clipkeys simply send a [RAMIGA-c] to
the system.  This does a generic Copy command, then CBE will copy this
data into the specified unit for that key.
  For pasting just the opposite is done.  CBE will copy the data from
the selected clipkey into clipboard unit 0, then CBE will send an
[RAMIGA-v] key sequence, thus pasting the data to your application.

  Pretty simple isn't it.  Now why wasn't this done years ago??!!??!!

  OK, so you now have a program such as PowerSnap/SnapIt, or even
Terminus.  These programs copy the data without you needing to hit
[RAMIGA-c].  In fact you cannot even if you wanted to.  So, does CBE's
clipkeys work with these programs?  Of course, but you must do things
in a silghtly different way.... Normally you highlight the text, then
press the key combination to Copy the data.  Well since there is no
time allowed for yo to do this, simply press the clipkey sequence
BEFORE you highlight or box the text from these programs.  If nothing
is available for the clipboard when a copy command is sent, the syetem
will wait until something is sent to the clipboard device.  CBE will
then intercept this and put the data into the correct slot.
  I wish I could take credit for this, but it is a fine side effect of
the clipboard device itself.

@endnode


@node Weird "Wierd Things/Bug List"
@font Courier.font 15


     @{b}Weird things / Bug list@{ub}

@font Courier.font 13
  o  There are no know bugs in this version of CBE.

  1: I wrote CBE to have an 11 line listview box.  Some systems will
     display a 10 line box with one reccessed box underneath that
     shows the selected item.
  A: Some version of the operating system do not abide by the rules
     laid down in the ROM Kernal Manuals. (??) I used the functions as
     described, but apparently they do not all work that way.

  2: Some have complained about Enforcer hits when view a clipboard
     unit with MultiView.
  A: I get these errors when I run MulwiView on it's own.  Actually
     for me, the datatypes give the errors.  For this reason I do not
     feel it is my program that is at fault, and there is no way for
     me to debug this until I get a working MultiView.
     This is what i do:

     ------ START --------
     ULONG ViewGClicked()     // Run MultiView
     {
          static UBYTE cmd[128];
          BPTR ifh;
          BPTR ofh;

          sprintf(cmd, "Sys:Utilities/MultiView CLIPBOARD CLIPUNIT %d", unit);

          ifh=Open("NIL:",MODE_NEWFILE);
          if( ifh )
          {
               ofh=Open("NIL:",MODE_OLDFILE);
               if( ofh )
               {
                    SystemTags(cmd, SYS_Input, ifh, SYS_Output, ofh,
                                             SYS_Asynch, TRUE, TAG_DONE);
                    return(TRUE);
               }
               Close(ifh);
          }
          PrintError("Could not open I/O for Viewer");
          return(FALSE);
     }
     ----- END ----------
     I have tried using Execute, I have tried opening file handles to
     actual files as well.  NOTHING helps.  If anyone knows why this fails, 
     I would REALLY like to knnow.


  3: The title bar of MultiView has garbage in it!!  Fix It!!
  A: Well once again, I have no control over the title bar in
     MultiView, so I have no way of fixing the problem.
     (You may change the TXTVIEW/SNDPLAY/GFXVIEW to use MultiView, and
      the title bar will show the clipboard number being shown.  When
      viewing a clip unit this way, I actually access the file "CLIPS:xx".)

  Please report any bugs, enforcer or mungwall hits.  I need your
help to make CBE the best possible program for all users. Any suggestions
for appearence, or usefullness are always welcome.

     CBE has been tested on:
          A3000/030 OS2.04
          A1200/020 OS3.0
          A2000/020 OS2.1
          A4000/040 OS3.1

     CBE was created on:
          A1200 w/ CSA's 12-Guage 50MHz 68030/68882 with 8M Fast RAM,
               420M of HD space, external 880K floppy, internal 1440K
               floppy, Chinon-535 CD-ROM, Archive-Viper tape backup unit,
               Supra 14.4 modem, HP500 DeskJet...blah, blah, blah...

     and was written in C and assembly using SAS/C 6.51, about a case of Mt Dew
     each day, about a half dozen pizzas, and very little sleep.

@endnode

@node Revisions "Revisions"
@font Courier.font 15


   @{b}Revisions:  ( '-' =Bug fixes, '+' =Additions or improvments.)@{ub}
@font Courier.font 13

   V2.3 (24-Mar-94)+Added @{"ARexx" link ARexx} commands.
                   +Added Menus.  Uses KS3.x NewLook if possible.
                   +Put Registration info to Quit requester.
                   +Close Gadget hides window immediately on registered version.
                   +New documentaion. Hopefully more coherent.
                   +Added '»' character to end of display to show long lines.
                   +Added @{"FIXFONT" link ToolTypes 24} tooltype to widen GUI for bad fonts.
                   +Added window ZOOM gadget.  Registered version can set exact
                    location of @{"ZOOM" link ToolTypes 15} window.

   V2.2 (16-Mar-94)-Update would not relocate Locks correctly.
                   +Added PUBSCRNAME @{"ToolTypes" link ToolTypes}.

   V2.1 (14-Mar-94)-Empty clipboard units should now be displayed with correct
                    information in the display.  I made some incorrect
                    assumtions about how clipboard data was stored.  I just got
                    ahold of the RKM:Devices manual.  Things look good now.
                    Just because a clipboard unit is empty, does not mean
                    there is no data in it. :-(
                    Funny, I never saw these problems even though the tests I
                    ran should have caused these problems easily. Just Lucky(?)
                   +When the hotkey is pressed, or when an attempt to start
                    CBE a second time is made, the user interface window will
                    always be brought to the front, whether it is already open
                    or not, even if it is on another screen.  This is done
                    cleanly, meaning it will not close down before re-opening
                    if it does not need to.  Unlike some other commodities.
                   +Clear gadget added.  You may now clear any/all units.
                   +Added Jump button to 'Jump' to next screen.
                   +Free/Lock now in a cycle gadget.  To make room for Update.
   V2.0 Not quite  +Update gadget added to update list on the fly.
    ready to be    +Reserved keys will now always be the last units in the list
    released.       when first run.  CBE would always start them at 10 units
                    from the end no matter how many there were.
                   -If you started CBE for the first time, it was possible that
                    garbage would appear in the list the first time it was run.
                   +If you used the commodity Exchange program to Inactivate
                    then re-activate, CBE would Always re-read and copy
                    data from Unit 0 and put it into unit 1.  This no longer
                    happens unless the data has actualy changed since CBE
                    has gone inactive.
                   +Fixed problem when Pasting from Clipkey, you were then not
                    able to put the first review line back into the clipboard
                    without first moving it down, then up.
                   +CBE is now font sensitive, and preferences font aware.
                   +Changed "<EMPTY>" to "[##]" for esthetics.
                   +You may now select to open CBE on the frontmost screen.
                    This is NOT system friendly, but frequently requested.
                   +The Quit/Hide/Cancel requester pops up at the window's
                    location, and on the same screen if that changes.
                   +You may now specify opening position for the window, if no
                    position is given, it will open under the mouse.
                   +New clipped data will now go into the _First Empty_ unit
                    before pulling an unlocked unit from the end of the list.
                   -For some reason CBE was unfriendly with prefrences.  If you
                    changed screen modes, the screen may redraw 3 or more times
                    then finally end with a requester asking you to close all
                    open windows.  This would happen even while CBE was hidden.
                   +The icon is now drawn to better fit the system default
                    colors rather than my twisted idea of what looks good.
                   +Added requester to display errors such as "Need OS2.0"...
                   +Minimal code optimizations/cleanup.
                    '-' now displayed for any LOCKed unit.  Updates correctly.
                   +Highlighted bar in LstView no longer moves when new clips
                    are put into the list.  Seems cleaner to me.

   V1.21 (8-Mar-94)-STUPID bug when clipping to key.  Ooopps, must have hit the
                    UNDO just before saving or something???
                   +Changed order of HIDE/CANCEL in quit requester. Now pressing
                    escape will close the commodity window. Requested change.

   V1.2  (8-Mar-94)+Removed the cripplware limit of 5 clipboard units.
                   -Fixes reported "bug" where an output window would open on
                    some, but not all systems. Never found the cause.

   V1.1  (7-Mar-94)+Added Hot KEY, you may now bring the window up at any time.
   (Unreleased)    +You may now use the function keys (or others as  specified)
                    to Copy/Paste from up to 10 clipboard units.
                   +Lock/free now work.
                   +Icon now included.  I dont know HOW I missed it last time.
                   +More, but I forget, it's been a rough week with work, etc..
                   -Fixed misc bugs.

   V1.0  (5-Mar-94) First release.
                   -Fixed errors in commodity/window signals.  If you did
                    things in the wrong order, all available clipboard units
                    would be filled with the current data from unit 0.
                   +Removed the useless info from the List display.

   ß0.6  (3-Mar-94)+Beta release.  Now runs as a commodity, from either
                    the CLI, or from Workbench. You can now specify programs
                    for viewing Gfx, Text, and playing sounds.

   ß0.5  (3-Mar-94)+First Beta version.  Limited use.

   ß0.1  (1-Mar-94) Simple test version.

@endnode

